title: For Sale/Trade:  Greg Christian Tennessee 54 cal
postcontent:
OK....I have a bad case of wanting a fur trapper era Northwest Trade Rifle, so I am regrettably putting up my Greg Christian 54cal Tennessee for sale.

 Fancy maple stock.

 Green Mountain rifled, octagon to round barrel with wedding band at 42 inches.

 Chambers Late Ketland Lock,very fast and sparks like the 4th of July.

 Tennessee style rifle with custom ordered musket style buttstock...much more comfortable to shoulder and shoot.

 59 inches over all and points well. 

 Finished in Aqua-Fortis with 10 coats of hand rubbed boiled lindseed oil...Not the fake stuff!

 All browned furniture.

 Mirror bore...sharp lands and grooves...I take care of my bores...I didn't order the round counter attachment, but I would guesstimate about 300 rounds...FFF Goex only. 

 Simple, beautiful, and accurate...It is a joy to shoot. 

 About 6 years old, but looks 150...in a good way!

 A few very light handling marks, but certainly no cracks.

 I also am throwing in a Lee 5 cavity .520 mold and about 3/500 pure lead cast round balls, as this is the only rifle I have that shoots the 520 ball best...I use a 1000 patch.

 Green Mountain barrels are notoriously tight. You can stuff a 525 or 530 down it and do just fine, but why fight it?

  Would prefer to meet at Sapulpa/Bristow/Glenpool China Marts during daylight hours. I will however, if your seriously interested, drive up to 75 miles to meet you for a no obligation look. No tire kickers or BSers, please. We must agree on terms b4 meeting.

 Asking $950.00 FTF cash for everything. This is probably about half the replacement cost...not counting extras.

 I'm not a good photographer, but I have some more pics I can email on request.

Would rather sell for cash, as I have a new Northwest Trade rifle to pay for, but I am a hopeless accumulator of quality firearms, so send me partial/full trade offer if you like. If we cannot trade, all I can do is give you a polite, No Thanks.

 Have a good day and tnx for looking. 

  NRA LIFE

title: For Sale:  1942 Colt M1911A1 .45 ACP U.S. Army Single Action
postcontent:
This 1942 Colt Single Action U.S. Army .45 Caliber ACP Model M1911A1 has been examined and tested and is in very good condition.

Make: Colt 

Model: M1911A1 

Serial Number: 852297

Year of Manufacture: 1942 – The initials of WB inside a Box for Colonel Waldemar S. Broberg, Hartford/Springfield Ordnance District, Army Inspector of Ordnance: July 1, 1941 - June 16, 1942, signifying government acceptance of the pistol.

Caliber: .45 ACP 

Action Type: Single Action, Semi-Automatic with Removable Magazine 

Markings: The left side of the slide is marked “PATENTED APR.20.1897 SEPT.9.1902. / DEC.19.1905.FEB.14.1911.AUG.19.1913”, “COLTS PT. F.A. MFG. CO. / HARTFORD. CT. U.S.A.” and with the Rampant Colt logo in the center. 

The left of the frame near the magazine release is marked with a “P” acceptance proof and under the slide release with a boxed “W.B.” (Waldemar Broberg, Col., USA Colt Ordnance Sub-Inspector for Colt M1911A1 .45 Auto Pistols 1942.) The right side of the frame is marked “UNITED STATES PROPERTY / No "852297” (NOTE: There is a significant wear mark from a resting index finger over the Serial Number. This is NOT a grind mark), “M1911A1 U.S. ARMY”. The slot on the right underside of the slide is marked “5” and the flat at the very rear of the slide is marked with what appears to be “J”. The top of the slide in front of the rear sight is marked “P”. The left side of the barrel lug is marked with a “P”, and the barrel above the lug is marked “Colt 45 AUTO” (markings as used from Serial No. 750,000 to the end of production in 1945). The inside of the left “Coltwood” grip is marked “8”. The inside of the right "Coltwood" grip is marked "T" or "1" (Not clear). The upper and the lower retain the identical serial numbers.

Barrel Length: 5” 

Sights / Optics: The front sight is a short serrated ramped blade fixed to the slide. The rear sight is a square notch dovetailed into the slide. 

Stock Configuration & Condition: The grips are checkered reddish brown plastic. The checkering in the left grip is sharp. The checkering in the right grip is sharp. Light wear at the bottom of the grip on both sides. The grips rate in about Very Good overall condition. 

Type of Finish: The finish is in fair to good condition. The mainspring housing is checkered. 

Finish Originality: This pistol originally had a Parkerized finish.

Bore Condition: The bore is bright and the rifling is sharp. There is no erosion in the bore. 

Overall Condition: Good

Mechanics: The trigger pull is crisp. The slide is tight on the frame. The action functions correctly. We have fired this pistol and it functions as expect with no malfunction after 7 rounds. 

Box, Paperwork & Accessories: One (1) magazine is provided. Unknown manufacturer, however this magazine was stored with the weapon for over 40 years. 

Our Assessment: > The 1911 and 1911-A1 pistols served the military of the United States from 1911 to 1985, through two World Wars and the Korean and Vietnam wars. They gained a reputation as a reliable handgun with plenty of stopping power, and are held in high regard by those who have used them. This is a WWII manufactured 1911A1 pistol made by Colt and is part of a group delivered to the U. S. Hartford/Springfield Ordnance District, Army Inspector of Ordnance. It is in about Very Good condition, with thinning and handling marks over about 10% of its finish with little pitting. It is missing its magazine. This weapon has a great bore. This weapon will provide a wonderful addition to any collection!

We have two dozen pictures. Please email us if you wish to see more pictures or discuss the weapon. mmonetta "at" dssinc "dot" org. I can also be reached at REDACTED

I have seen many of these exact weapons and this unit is the best condition weapon we have ever seen! I have confirmed this statement with a variety of other Colt owners!

Local Face to Face Cash Transactions Only. You will be required to provide valid state id. All id information will be recorded on "Transfer of Ownership" document. Signed original copies will be provided for both seller and buyer.

postcontent: With its construction of ultra high performance and tough Stainless Steel, the Spectre 22 allows weapon fire to go virtually unnoticed.It is not only super tough, but also one of the quietest .22 suppressors known to man. With the Spectre 22, users will also enjoy its multi-caliber versatility.The Spectre 22 has a unique CTA baffle design for easy disassembly and is user serviceable, which is very important for any .22 lr silencer. Because the .22 lr round is not copper jacketed, molten lead and carbon debris will explode into the silencer when the projectile exits the muzzle. After some time it is possible for a .22 suppressor to fill completely with lead and become heavy and ineffective. To avoid this issue .22 silencers must be able to be disassembled for cleaning and regularly maintained. Most .22 silencers on the market can be disassembled for cleaning, however they require cleaning every 50 to 200 rounds or often times they will fuse together and they are unable to come apart. When the lead and carbon debris adhere to the inner wall of the silencer tube and fill the spaces between the baffles and the tube, there is simply too much build up of fouling and lead to remove the tube from most .22 lr silencers on the market. The Spectre 22 has the unique CTA baffle design that keeps the carbon and lead debris from reaching the silencer tube allowing it to be disassembled easily.SPECTRE 22CALIBER:.22 LR.17 HMR.22 MAG.22 WMR.22 HORNETFN 5.7X28WEIGHT:6.8 OZDIAMETER1.000”LENGTH:5.98”AVG SOUND LEVEL:.22LR – 113.8 dB.17HMR- 123.3 dB5.7×28- 125.8 dBFINISH:Black OxideMATERIALS:Baffles & End Caps: 17-4 Stainless SteelTube: 316 Stainless SteelThread Mount: 17-4 Stainless SteelFEATURES:Full Auto Rated for .22 LRDurable Stainless SteelChemical ResistantLifetime WarrantyUser Serviceable with CTA Baffles

postcontent: 687 Silver Pigeon III - Premium Looks, Features, Value: The Silver Pigeon III over-under hunting shotgun is the mid-level offering of the Beretta Silver Pigeon line. It has all the benefits of the Silver Pigeon I plus more extensive game engraving and a stock oval for the owner’s initials, while not featuring the gold inlays of the Silver Pigeon V. Weighing only about 7 lbs, it handles wonderfully as a game gun while not being too light for a long session at the clay range. It is available in 12 and 20 gauge, or in 28 gauge with a petite scaled frame. Natural Pointability, Swing: The Silver Pigeon is built on the legendary 687 action, a long-standing favorite among hunters and competitive shooters. It features two conical locking lugs at mid-action, right between the barrels, giving it great locking strength and durability while keeping the action’s profile considerably lower. The advantage is that the eye of the shooter is a lot closer to the plane of his supporting hand, resulting in a considerably better swing and hand-eye coordination. Tough, Accurate Barrels: The Silver Pigeon III is a shotgun designed to last several lifetimes in spite of its lightness and fast handling.
